Chapter 2.7
In the past, Ning Sinian never returned home before midnight. Now, at precisely 5:30 PM, he would pack up his briefcase and leave.

As the hour approached, Qin Li hurriedly called the two children back. Meanwhile, Zhou Yunsheng noticed that the moment he left, Zhao Jun had installed numerous surveillance cameras on the trees by the lake. He couldn’t help but marvel at the man’s sycophantic dedication.

“How was your day?” Ning Sinian, after sending Qin Li off, entered the house, kissed his son’s forehead, then naturally cupped the teenager’s face and kissed him as well, as if such intimacy had always existed between them.

At first, Zhou Yunsheng was taken aback, but over time, he grew accustomed to it. He merely pressed his lips together and gave a slight nod, remaining silent. As if you don’t already know how our day was, you pervert.

Hearing movement, Zhao Xinfang came downstairs and eagerly took Ning Sinian’s suit jacket and briefcase. The two of them exchanged affectionate smiles, their arms wrapped around each other’s waists, resembling a deeply devoted couple.

Except for Ning Wangshu, this entire family was full of award-winning actors.

After dinner, Ning Sinian coaxed his son to sleep and intended to have a conversation with Wei Xiyan to build their rapport. However, he soon realized that the boy had already slipped away and even locked his door.

Had he not been misled and treated the boy so coldly before, Xiyan would never have been this wary of him. Ning Sinian ran a hand through his hair in frustration, deeply regretting his past actions and harboring a simmering resentment toward Zhao Xinfang. But since Qian Yu still had his uses, Ning Sinian had no choice but to bide his time.

The teenager retrieved an art book from the shelf, spread it open on the bed, and sat cross-legged, making notes as he flipped through the pages. Ning Sinian watched him with a soft smile for a moment. Since it was still early, he opened his laptop to handle some work.

Time slipped away unnoticed. At 10:30 PM, his phone let out a faint beep, pulling him from his tasks.

Ning Sinian dismissed the alarm and glanced at the screen. As expected, the boy, who adhered to a precise schedule, was undressing, preparing for a warm shower before bed.

The white shirt slid off his shoulders, revealing the elegant contours of his shoulder blades. His waist was lean yet supple, and his hips were perfectly shaped. With just one glance, Ning Sinian abruptly averted his eyes, suddenly restless.

He stood up, made himself a cup of coffee, and paced the study, listening to the sound of water cascading in the bathroom.

Irritation gnawed at him. He unfastened the top two buttons of his shirt and finally returned to his desk, gripping his coffee cup tightly while forcing himself to focus on the screen.

He had to admit—he anticipated this moment every night. What kind of deviant had he become? He cursed himself inwardly, yet he couldn’t stop.

Setting down the coffee, he lit a cigarette, hoping the smoke would blur his vision. But it was unnecessary—the rising steam from the bathroom had already fogged up the surveillance camera, leaving only a faint silhouette of ivory.

And yet, Ning Sinian found himself dissatisfied again, cursing under his breath.

The water finally stopped. His cigarette had burned down, and he had been so absorbed that the embers nearly scorched his fingers. He let out a string of curses, crushing the cigarette into the ashtray.

The bathroom door opened. The boy emerged, hair damp, wearing only an oversized white shirt that barely covered his thighs. His long, slender legs were fully exposed.

His feet were delicate, perfectly shaped. As he stepped onto the plush wool carpet, his toes curled slightly—a small, unconscious movement that was unbearably endearing.

Years of painting had left his skin porcelain-white, with faint blue veins visible beneath the delicate surface. He looked soft, fragile.

One last time. This is the last time. Tomorrow, he would remove all the cameras.

Ning Sinian reassured himself with this habitual lie, then abandoned all resistance, raising his cup as he indulged in his stolen gaze.

A sharp knock shattered the moment—it was Zhao Jun.

His hands trembled, spilling half his coffee onto his shirt and trousers.

Shit! He shot to his feet, grabbing tissues to clean himself, only to realize the stiffness between his legs.

Shit! He froze, then cursed himself viciously, raking his fingers through his hair. He knew if this continued, he would eventually cross a line he couldn’t return from, yet he was powerless against his own depravity.

“Come in.” He sat down, his face bleak, his tone hollow.

In that brief moment of distraction, the boy on the screen curled his lips into a quick, fleeting smirk, mouthing a silent goodnight—

"Goodnight, pervert."

The two-month summer break passed swiftly. Ning Sinian lived in a constant state of torment, feeling utterly drained.

Maybe I should find a way to distance myself from Wei Xiyan.

He told himself this repeatedly, only to soon contradict his own resolve.

“What are you packing for?” His expression darkened as he saw the boy descending the stairs, dragging a suitcase.

“I’m moving into the school dorms.” Zhou Yunsheng instinctively hid the suitcase behind him, looking somewhat nervous.

Ning Sinian cleared his throat and softened his voice. “How often will you come home?”

“I’ll be back during winter break.”

Winter break? That meant at least three to four months away.

A sharp buzzing filled Ning Sinian’s mind. “Absolutely not. You’re not staying in the dorms.” He had already forgotten his previous resolve to keep his distance.

You’re addicted, aren’t you, you sick pervert? Zhou Yunsheng sneered internally but outwardly widened his eyes in feigned innocence, looking both aggrieved and frightened.

Bathed in the boy’s dewy gaze, Ning Sinian felt his entire body go numb, heat creeping up his ears. But his expression remained stern as he declared, “No. You lack basic self-care skills. Once you start painting, you lose track of time and even forget your meals. You’re staying home—I’ll drive you to and from school every day. Otherwise, I won’t be able to rest easy.”

Zhou Yunsheng sat in the farthest corner, silently staring at the breakfast placed in front of him.

His temper was truly stubborn. Ning Sian had no way to deal with him and could only look at his son, "Baby, your uncle is going to school and won't be back to see you for three or four months. Will you miss him?"

Ning Wangshu finally realized the severity of the situation, immediately jumping off his chair and running over to Zhou Yunsheng. His little hands clung tightly to his pants legs, his face filled with a heart-wrenching expression, as if on the verge of tears.

Such a perverted man, even using his own son. Zhou Yunsheng almost wanted to wipe his face but managed to hold back.

"If you're not staying at school, you'll need to go through the formalities for day school," he said slowly.

"Okay, I'll go take care of it for you in a bit." Ning Sian was finally satisfied, taking the opportunity to sit next to the teenager and happily kissed his son, "Good boy, you're really making your daddy proud."

Zhao Xinfang, who was pretending to cook congee in the kitchen while wearing an apron, heard the commotion and her face darkened. More than two months had passed, and not only had Ning Wangshu started to return to normal, but even Ning Sian's attitude towards Wei Xiyan had drastically changed. When Wei Xiyan first arrived, Ning Sian treated him like air, but now he spoiled him like a treasure.

What was going on? Did he forget how Wei Xiyan treated Ning Wangshu? Or did he know the truth? No, if he knew, how could he be pampering Wang Ma and even taking time out of his day to personally visit the hospital? It must be those two old fools protecting Wei Xiyan, and he had no choice. Now that their relationship was growing closer, what if one day during a conversation, Wei Xiyan revealed what happened at the hotel entrance?

No, I must get rid of Wei Xiyan as soon as possible!

Zhao Xinfang's mind raced, and she thought of a brilliant idea.

Wei Xiyan was a freshman at the Kyoto Academy of Fine Arts. He didn’t take the college entrance exam; instead, Ning's father had a famous oil painter from France write a letter of recommendation, and he was specially recruited.

Ning Sian sent his assistant to take care of the day-school formalities and went to the dorm to help Wei Xiyan pack.

"I'll do it. You stay there," he said as he removed his suit jacket, rolled up his sleeves, and stacked a few large art books, preparing to move them all at once.

As the male lead, Ning Sian's looks were naturally outstanding. He wasn’t as flawless and handsome as Du Xulang, but he exuded a powerful masculinity. Standing almost 190 cm tall, his long legs were always in Zhou Yunsheng's sight, making him dizzy. His thin shirt perfectly outlined his muscular build.

This man was pure, moving testosterone.

Zhou Yunsheng clearly realized this and had to divert his gaze elsewhere.

"Are you hot? Your face is all red. It's so much more comfortable at home with air conditioning." The boy's cheeks were flushed, his eyes shining, making Ning Sian's mouth dry. Taking the chance to speak, he leaned in and pinched the tip of his nose.

Zhou Yunsheng lowered his eyes and nodded, his shy demeanor making Ning Sian itch with desire.

After putting the art books and brushes together in a cardboard box, Ning Sian carried the box with one hand and held the teenager’s hand with the other, walking slowly toward the parking lot.

"Xi Yan, you’re here for the registration?"

As Ning Sian opened the trunk to place the things, Zhou Yunsheng heard someone calling and looked over. His eyes instantly darkened with a wicked smile. He recognized the person—it was Wei Xiyan's senior, Fu Xuan. After leaving the Ning family, Wei Xiyan had a chance to bounce back, but it was ruined by this man. He plagiarized Wei Xiyan's painting and submitted it to the International Oil Painting Awards, winning the top prize and becoming famous.

This incident was the final straw that broke Wei Xiyan.

Zhou Yunsheng squinted his eyes and walked up to him, respectfully greeting, "Senior." Fu Xuan knew he was going for day-school registration and took the opportunity to remind him to show him his competition work if there were any problems, and he could give some suggestions.

Zhou Yunsheng nodded, not saying much. Fu Xuan noticed a man parking his car at the roadside, smoking while staring at him with malicious eyes, and he felt uneasy. He quickly found an excuse to leave.

"Who is he?" Ning Sian asked sternly after they got in the car.

"Senior," Zhou Yunsheng replied, blinking his watery peach blossom eyes.

Ning Sian's sour feelings evaporated, but he still mumbled, "He talks too much."

Zhou Yunsheng, choking on the smoke in the car, couldn't help but frown and said, "Put out the cigarette."

Ning Sian immediately snuffed out the cigarette and raised both hands in a gesture of surrender. His smooth and natural reaction made both of them freeze for a moment.

Zhou Yunsheng stared at him for a while, trying to find any familiar trace on his handsome face but to no avail. The drive back was filled with an awkward silence.


