Chapter 2.8
Du Xulang was just a string of data written by the main god. Unlike himself, who possessed an immortal soul, how could he possibly follow him here? A man smoking a cigarette was normal, and having similar small habits was also normal.

Zhou Yunsheng convinced himself of this, but a bitter feeling lingered in his heart.

However, he soon had no time to dwell on it, as Fu Xuan called him repeatedly, urging him to submit his painting for the Oil Painting Grand Prize as soon as possible. His tone was filled with an urgency he could hardly conceal.

Fu Xuan was considered a prominent figure in the oil painting department, backed by a powerful family. His father was the president of the C Nation’s Calligraphy and Painting Association, while his mother was an internationally renowned oil painter specializing in landscapes. Her masterpiece Wheat Waves had once been auctioned for a staggering 7.5 million at Jiadeli Auction House. Having inherited his parents' exceptional genes, Fu Xuan held his first solo exhibition at the age of six, and in painting, his talent surpassed everyone else.

However, cases of prodigies falling from grace were not uncommon, and unfortunately, Fu Xuan became a textbook example of this. Having achieved success too early, he grew arrogant. Surrounded by swarms of admirers, he gradually lost his motivation to improve. Instead of honing his skills, he indulged in a life of pleasure.

Artistic skills require constant refinement. Going too long without practice leads to a loss of inspiration and technique. When Fu Xuan realized he could no longer even draw a simple line in front of his canvas, he finally panicked.

But instead of forcing himself to pick up the brush again, he resorted to hiring ghostwriters. Any assignments or competition entries assigned by his instructors were done by others. The oil painting department had no shortage of exceptionally talented yet financially struggling students. Fu Xuan sought out the most discreet among them, offering money in exchange for their work. This arrangement benefited both parties, allowing him to coast smoothly through four years of university and even be regarded as one of the top students by his professors.

However, the International Oil Painting Grand Prize was a major event in the art world, held only once every five years. Even Fu Xuan’s ghostwriter had secured a spot and saw it as a chance to make a name for himself, thus refusing to help him this time.

Left with no choice, Fu Xuan set his sights on Wei Xiyan.

Wei Xiyan was withdrawn and low-key, rarely interacting with his classmates. Naturally, Fu Xuan had no knowledge of his family background and simply assumed he was an orphan with no support. So, he outright plagiarized his painting.

That particular piece had been Wei Xiyan’s outlet after being abandoned by the Ning family. He had poured all his resentment, pain, longing, and sorrow into it, breaking away from his usual steady style and seamlessly blending classical beauty with the free-spirited essence of abstract art. The result was stunning.

With this masterpiece, Wei Xiyan originally had the potential to become one of the greatest oil painters of his time. However, not only did Fu Xuan steal his work, but he also turned around and sued him for copyright infringement.

Having been cast out by the Ning family, Wei Xiyan had no means to fight back and was forced to settle out of court, agreeing to permanently withdraw from the world of oil painting.

The pain of never being able to pick up his beloved brush again was unimaginable, and in the end, Wei Xiyan lost the will to live.

Now, Zhou Yunsheng attended classes as a day student, painting in the studio at the Ning residence rather than alongside his peers. This made it difficult for Fu Xuan to steal his work. As the deadline for submission approached, Fu Xuan grew desperate and called several times, falsely claiming that their professor had asked him to collect everyone’s paintings.

Zhou Yunsheng agreed on the surface, but after hanging up, his gaze darkened.

He carefully studied the painting on his easel, made a few final adjustments, and waited for the paint to dry before bringing it to Ning Sinian’s study.

It was the weekend, and Ning Sinian was working from home. He reviewed thick stacks of documents with focus, but every ten minutes, he would glance at the surveillance feed, feeling reassured each time he saw the boy standing at his easel as usual.

The boy wasn’t going anywhere. He would always stay in place, waiting for him.

The thought struck him suddenly, yet it filled him with deep satisfaction.

When he snapped back to reality, the studio was empty, and a familiar sense of restlessness surged within him. If this were at his office, he would have immediately called Zhao Jun to search for him. But since it was his day off, he decided to go himself.

Just as he set down his documents, a knock came at the door.

“Who is it?” he asked impatiently.

“It’s me.” The boy’s voice was clear and melodious.

Ning Sinian froze for a split second, then quickly shut off the surveillance feed on his computer. He hastily organized the scattered documents on his desk and, upon reaching the door, paused to check his reflection in the glass cabinet, ensuring that he looked impeccably handsome before finally opening the door with a smile.

“Xiyan, come in.”

He naturally took hold of the boy’s pale wrist and led him to the loveseat. At first, he intended to pour a cup of coffee, but for some reason, that didn’t seem appropriate. Instead, he went downstairs to the kitchen and carefully prepared a warm glass of milk, bringing it up with great care.

Zhou Yunsheng was thoroughly enjoying being pampered but kept up an expression of surprise and shyness. His cheeks were flushed, and with his bright, watery peach blossom eyes, he looked so captivating that Ning Sinian nearly lost control.

Suppressing his inner turmoil, Ning Sinian sat close beside him and asked softly, “Xiyan, did you need something?” If not, the boy would never voluntarily come near him.

“Mm.” Zhou Yunsheng timidly glanced at him, pursing his lips before whispering, “I want to participate in the Oil Painting Grand Prize.”

“The Oil Painting Grand Prize? I know about it. Are there no more spots? I’ll make a call right now and get you straight into the finals.” Seizing the chance to do him a favor, Ning Sinian eagerly dialed a number, about to press the call button.

The Ning Corporation was the event’s biggest sponsor—securing a final round entry was effortless.

“No, that’s not it.” Zhou Yunsheng hurriedly grabbed his arm, his face turning bright red. “I already have a spot.”

Taking advantage of the moment, Ning Sinian pulled him into an embrace, gently stroking his soft hair. He barely contained his excitement as he asked, “Then what’s wrong?”

Damn pervert, his tricks for copping a feel are practically divine. Zhou Yunsheng gritted his teeth inwardly but lowered his head and mumbled, “Can I submit this painting?”

Only then did Ning Sinian notice the 22x14 painting frame at his feet. He lifted the protective cover and was greeted by the sight of Ning Wangshu’s chubby little face.

The young child was squatting on the ground, wearing an oversized white shirt with the sleeves rolled up high. He raised his plump little hands, covered in paint, proudly displaying them to the artist. Beside him lay a canvas full of tiny handprints. To him, this was clearly a masterpiece, and his bright, beaming smile reflected his delight—so much so that even the sunlight filtering into the background couldn’t compare.

The artist had poured all their love and tenderness into every brushstroke. Warm tones dominated the canvas, exuding hope, joy, tranquility, and an overwhelming sense of vibrant happiness. The moment the painting was unveiled, it seemed to radiate pure warmth.

Ning Sinian was stunned. He had almost forgotten the last time he saw his son’s smiling face.

“Can I submit this painting for review?” Zhou Yunsheng gently touched his arm.

Ning Sinian finally came back to his senses, blinking his sore eyes. “Yes, of course.” He paused for a moment before adding, “Someday, you should paint a portrait for me too.”

He would never admit that he was even jealous of his own son.

“Okay.” Zhou Yunsheng nodded, carefully covering the painting with a protective sleeve.

When Fu Xuan saw Zhou Yunsheng bringing his work for submission, he looked as if he had found a savior. He studied the painting for a long time, and upon learning that the child in the artwork was purely imaginary, he finally let out a sigh of relief. He knew this painting would stand out—it was incredibly vivid, filled with spirit and emotion, a labor of love poured into every stroke.

