"Once this deal is done, I’ll leave the country to lay low. Keep an eye on Ning Sinian for me. Let me know if anything happens," he said, pocketing the drive. Then he grabbed Zhao Xinfang’s chest playfully before hurrying away.

Ning Sinian stood in the messy study, his stomach churning.

The files Qian Yu had just stolen contained critical errors. If he sold them to a rival company, that company would suffer losses worth billions. All Ning Sinian had to do was wait for the right moment to strike and reap the benefits.

He forced himself to return to work, but he couldn't sit still. Every few minutes, he pulled up the surveillance feed to check on the young man.

At last, when the clock struck 5:30, he immediately packed up and left for home.

By the lake, Qin Li was feeding ducks with Ning Wangshu. The young man was nowhere to be seen. Ning Sinian hurriedly greeted them before rushing inside.

"What are you doing?" His voice was sharp, with an unmistakable tremor beneath it.

Zhou Yunsheng paused for a moment, then continued packing his suitcase.

Based on Wei Xiyan’s personality, after what had happened today, he would never dare to tell Ning Sinian, let alone stay in the Ning residence. But Zhou Yunsheng was just putting on a show—he needed to put some pressure on Ning Sinian, forcing him to deal with that woman sooner.

Honestly, Ning Sinian was quite useful. Zhou Yunsheng only needed to blink and pout, and he would take care of everything for him.

"Stop. Right. Now."

Ning Sinian impatiently knocked the clothes out of his hands. But when he saw the young man's startled, wide-eyed expression, he immediately softened. He pulled him into his arms and murmured, "Xiyan, I’m sorry. I didn’t mean to scare you. I just... don’t want you to leave. Tell me what happened today."

Zhou Yunsheng shook his head slightly, saying nothing.

Ning Sinian didn’t dare to push him, but his heart felt like it was being fried in boiling oil. He recalled Zhao Xinfang’s forceful kiss, and his eyes gradually turned bloodshot.

Why?

Why can I only watch him from the shadows, while others can touch him at will? Even forcefully steal a kiss from him?

The rage that had been simmering inside him finally exploded. He grasped the young man’s chin and rubbed his thumb harshly over his lips. Over and over again.

Zhou Yunsheng winced at the pain and instinctively tried to turn his head away—only for Ning Sinian to suddenly press in and capture his lips in a searing kiss. His tongue forced its way in, deep and demanding, as if he wanted to devour him whole.

Saliva trickled from the corner of their lips, forming a thin silver thread.

It lasted a long, long time—so long that Zhou Yunsheng could barely breathe. Only then did Ning Sinian reluctantly pull away. He didn’t move far, though; their lips were still touching, his fingers still gripping the young man’s chin as he stared into his eyes. His voice was hoarse and low.

"Tell me how you feel right now. Hmm?"

Like I want to fuck you. Zhou Yunsheng’s eyes gleamed mischievously, but he kept silent.

"Say it. Now."

Ning Sinian’s grip tightened, leaving faint bruises on the pale skin of his chin.

Zhou Yunsheng winced and slowly whispered, "I’m scared." Scared you won’t be able to perform, you crazy bastard.

The man leaned in even closer, his breath hot and intoxicating. His strong presence was overwhelming, nearly dizzying.

Zhou Yunsheng had always loved men like Ning Sinian—domineering, possessive, and wild. His ferocious touch and overwhelming desire were thrilling. Besides, that kiss had been amazing—it completely wiped away the disgust Zhao Xinfang left behind. Honestly, he wanted to thank him for it.

Ning Sinian panted heavily, his voice growing even rougher.

"Besides fear… what else?"

Zhou Yunsheng lowered his gaze, a faint blush rising to his cheeks. His dark eyes shimmered with unshed tears, making them look even more luminous and captivating.

Ning Sinian was entranced. His breath caught in his throat.

He’s shy.

He doesn’t find me disgusting. He… he feels something for me too.

Realizing this, it was as if he had finally found salvation after clinging to the edge of a cliff for so long. Relief and exhilaration surged through him. His tense nerves loosened, his sharp features softened, and his gaze overflowed with deep, boundless love.

"Xiyan… Xiyan… Xiyan…"

He murmured the young man’s name over and over, showering him with delicate kisses.

"Xiyan, baby, I love you. I love you so much. Can you understand? Can you feel it?"

The relationship with Ning Sinian naturally fell into place. No matter what changes might occur after the female lead appeared, Zhou Yunsheng didn’t care. He lived only in the present, cherishing this moment.

A month later, the Kyoto Academy of Fine Arts received news that out of the five paintings submitted for competition, one had made it to the final round and was now eligible to compete for the highest award. In such an esteemed art event, even the slightest association was like being gilded with gold, let alone having one’s work judged by master artists from around the world. It was an unparalleled honor.

The notification letter not only contained the selected artist’s name but also included a photograph of the painting. Students from the oil painting department eagerly passed it around.

"This is my painting. Why is it signed under Senior Brother’s name?" Zhou Yunsheng's face turned pale.

Everyone fell silent. Their shared mentor, Professor Tang Weiming, cast a severe gaze at him. "This painting was clearly created by Fu Xuan. I watched him complete it stroke by stroke. Why are you claiming it’s yours? Do you have any proof?"

Tang Weiming certainly knew who the real artist was. But having accepted benefits from Fu Xuan, he could only betray Wei Xiyan. The art world was not as pure and untainted as outsiders imagined—something Wei Xiyan would have to learn sooner or later.

"Yeah, we share the same studio with Senior Brother Fu Xuan. We saw him paint it with our own eyes." Several students chimed in, obviously having been bribed by Fu Xuan in advance.

Fu Xuan retrieved the notification letter, patted Zhou Yunsheng’s shoulder, and chuckled. "Junior Brother, you need evidence before making accusations. Otherwise, I could sue you for defamation."

Zhou Yunsheng seemed intimidated by the threat. His complexion was ashen, almost translucent. He cast a steady gaze at Tang Weiming, watching as the professor awkwardly averted his eyes. Then he looked at the classmates who had given false testimony before finally turning and walking away, step by step.

Fu Xuan let out a sigh of relief, knowing that as an orphan, Zhou Yunsheng had no power to fight back. He cheerfully announced that he would treat everyone to a meal. The students erupted in excitement, laughing and jostling as they made their way toward the school gate.

Zhou Yunsheng walked to a secluded corner, rubbed his eyes, cleared his throat, and then made a phone call.

His voice, thick with nasal congestion, startled Ning Sinian. Alarmed, he immediately asked, "Baby, what’s wrong? Did something happen? Don’t be afraid, I’m here. Tell me where you are, I’ll come right away."

Zhou Yunsheng’s hoarse voice came through the phone, "I’m at school. I feel terrible right now."

Ning Sinian comforted him while rushing downstairs to get his car. By the time he hung up, he was already on his way.

Zhou Yunsheng had the ability to deal with Fu Xuan, but right now, he was Wei Xiyan. Wei Xiyan’s world consisted only of painting—none of this filth. From the beginning, he had intended to let Ning Sinian handle all his troubles. After all, this was a debt Ning Sinian owed to Wei Xiyan—one that would have to be repaid sooner or later. As for Ning Sinian’s growing feelings for him, that was purely an accident.

Poor Fu Xuan had no idea what kind of terrifying person he had provoked.



——————————————————————————————————————————————————————————————————————


Chapter 2.10
Seeing the young man hiding in a corner, eyes red from tears, Ning Sinian was so furious he wanted to kill someone. He barely suppressed his anxiety, gently coaxing and persuading him to tell the truth before immediately taking him to the principal's office to file a complaint.

The principal dared not neglect the matter and quickly called Fu Xuan, Tang Weiming, and the others to his office.

When the group entered, their expressions haughty, Zhou Yunsheng pretended to be afraid, shrinking into Ning Sinian’s embrace and secretly clutching the corner of his coat. This small action only fueled Ning Sinian’s anger further, yet he still held him gently, patting his back reassuringly and whispering, “Don’t be scared.”

Tang Weiming and the others naturally recognized Ning Sinian’s face, which frequently graced the front pages of financial magazines. Seeing the intimate interaction between the two, a bad premonition rose in their hearts.

Ning Sinian wasted no time on pleasantries. Taking out his phone, he said, “I personally witnessed Xiyan painting the artwork ‘Brilliance’ stroke by stroke, yet for some reason, it is signed with Fu Xuan’s name. I’m here today to clarify this matter. To avoid any future misunderstandings, may I record our conversation?”

Refusing would be an admission of guilt. Fu Xuan had already coordinated with his mentor and classmates, so he thought recording wouldn't be a big deal. He nodded in agreement.

Tang Weiming, trembling, asked, “Mr. Ning, may I ask what your relationship with Wei Xiyan is?”

“What does my relationship with Xiyan have to do with you?” Ning Sinian sneered and turned to Fu Xuan, “When and where did you complete this painting? Who is the person in the painting?”

“I started painting in early September and finished by the end of October. I worked in the school studio the entire time, and my fellow students who share the studio can attest to this. The person in the painting doesn’t exist in reality—I imagined what my future child might look like, whether they’d inherit my artistic talent. With hope and love in my heart, I painted this child's face, stroke by stroke…”

Feeling guilty, Fu Xuan kept talking, rambling about his so-called artistic inspiration. The classmates he had bribed nodded in agreement, and even Tang Weiming added a few words to support him.

However, Zhou Yunsheng had actually started painting in mid-July and finished by the end of September. The entire painting process was recorded on Ning Sinian’s security cameras. Moreover, he had painted Ning Wangshu—one charge of image rights infringement alone was enough to ruin Fu Xuan.

Now, because of his own guilty conscience, Fu Xuan was speaking too much and making too many mistakes, all of which Ning Sinian recorded. Even if he wanted to retract his statements later, it would be impossible. He was walking himself straight into a dead end.

Ning Sinian didn’t interrupt him. Once he finished speaking, Ning proceeded to ask Tang Weiming a few questions, collecting solid evidence. Then, he took the young man’s hand, nodded at the principal, and said, “Principal Li, I’ll be taking my leave. My lawyers will handle this matter. I trust your school will ensure such incidents do not happen again in the future.”

“Of course, of course, Mr. Ning, please take care.” The principal respectfully escorted them to the door. Then, he turned back to stare at Fu Xuan for a long while before shaking his head. “Go home and ask your parents to hire the best lawyer they can find. If you're lucky, you might be able to negotiate a settlement.”

“Principal, why should I negotiate a settlement? That painting is mine! So many people can testify for me!” Fu Xuan refused to back down.

“Yours? So you painted Ning Sinian’s son from thousands of miles away? Imagining your future child while painting… Even I feel embarrassed for you.”

As soon as the principal finished speaking, Tang Weiming, who had been uneasy all along, felt his vision darken. The students who had given false testimony broke out in cold sweats, while Fu Xuan shrieked in disbelief. “How could this happen? Wei Xiyan told me that child was imaginary!”

The principal sighed internally—so it was true. Without hesitation, he threw them out of the office. Everyone involved in today’s fiasco was done for; their future was ruined.

Back home, Fu Xuan had no choice but to confess everything to his parents. But his family's influence was nothing compared to the Ning financial empire. Though the trial wasn’t public, and the media didn’t report on it to protect Ning Wangshu, the Fu family’s reputation in the art world was completely destroyed. After paying a huge compensation, they fled overseas, never to be heard from again.

As for Tang Weiming and the students who had given false testimony, they were also forced out of the oil painting circle, living out the rest of their lives in obscurity.

On the way home, Zhou Yunsheng hesitantly asked, “He had so many witnesses, but we only had the baby. Could we lose the case?”

“How could we? Our evidence is solid,” Ning Sinian reassured him, ruffling his soft hair.

“What evidence?” Zhou Yunsheng blinked innocently.

Ning Sinian broke out in a cold sweat but smiled. “Don’t worry. If I say we have evidence, we have evidence. You don’t need to concern yourself with the trial—I’ll handle everything. Do you have any other paintings? If so, pick one, and I’ll submit it to the competition for you.”

Zhou Yunsheng, satisfied with Ning Sinian’s nervous expression, nodded. “I have another painting of similar quality to ‘Brilliance.’ You can submit that one. By the way, can we avoid a public trial? I don’t want the baby’s life to be affected.”

The media would undoubtedly dig into the painting’s backstory, exposing Ning Wangshu to public scrutiny. He was still so young—such attention wouldn’t be good for him. Even though Zhou Yunsheng had the absolute ability to protect him, he still felt guilty for using his image.

Ning Sinian, unaware of the truth, only saw how much Zhou Yunsheng cared for his son, as if he were his own child. His heart softened, and he pulled him close, placing a gentle kiss on his forehead.

The two exchanged smiles, their eyes full of warmth.

When they got home, Zhou Yunsheng took Ning Wangshu to the lakeside to paint, while Ning Sinian called the Ning Corporation’s legal team. A civil case like this was child’s play for the country’s top law firm, and they promised to make the defendant pay the highest price.

After hanging up, Ning Sinian lit a cigar and stood by the window, gazing at the pair painting together. Just then, Zhao Xinfang stormed in, holding a credit card.

“Sinian, why are all my credit cards frozen?”

Ning Sinian turned around, his tone exceptionally gentle. “Xinfang, come take a look at this.”

Zhao Xinfang walked over and bent down to look at the computer screen. Ning Sinian clicked the play button, and in an instant, the room was filled with moans and gasps. Two pale bodies were intertwined in various acrobatic positions, the scene overwhelmingly decadent.

The color drained from Zhao Xinfang’s face. Staggering back a few steps, she stammered, “Sinian, I didn’t mean to... No, I was forced... Sinian, please don’t—”

Ning Sinian ignored her and picked up his phone to make a call.

About ten minutes later, several police officers knocked on the door and entered. They arrested Zhao Xinfang on charges of fraud, theft, and misappropriation of trade secrets. Given the enormous amount of money involved, she was sentenced to the maximum penalty and was ordered to pay an astronomical sum in compensation to the Ning Corporation. Additionally, the judge ruled to dissolve their marriage.

As for Qian Yu, he had already taken his own life a month earlier out of guilt.

Three years later, Dr. Qin Li retired, and Ning Sinian decided to hire a new housekeeper to take care of his partner and child. After all, both of them were obsessed with painting—once they stepped into the studio, they forgot everything else. Without someone to keep an eye on them, they might just starve themselves to death.

This was also why Ning Sinian refused to remove the surveillance cameras in the house.

That day, a beautiful young girl knocked on the door of the Ning residence.

“A-Ah! You... You’re Wei Xiyan? Wei Xiyan from The Way Home?” The girl pointed at the handsome young man’s face and exclaimed.

The Way Home was a painting submitted to an oil painting competition three years ago by Zhou Yunsheng as a gift to Wei Xiyan. It depicted a weary-looking boy lying on a woman’s lap. One of her hands gently combed through his hair, while the other cupped his face. Surrounding them were blooming roses, the breeze swirling around them, creating a warm and bright scene. Yet, behind the boy stretched an endless path of thorns.

His legs were curled up, his feet covered in blood, making it easy to imagine the arduous journey he had endured to reach the woman’s side. The painting, though surrealist in nature, carried a touch of classical romanticism, using warm hues to tell a heartbreaking story. The boy lay there quietly, his face so serene and beautiful that every passerby felt compelled to check his breathing—to see if he was still alive.

He was so young; he shouldn’t have had to bear everything alone. Everyone who saw the painting felt the urge to become the hands that embraced him.

When the painting was exhibited, so many people leaned in to check the boy’s breath that, to prevent damage, the organizers had to put up a sign next to it that read: He’s still alive!

The artist’s exceptional skill and raw emotion breathed life into the piece, winning it the highest award in the oil painting competition that year.

Wei Xiyan became an overnight sensation, but Ning Sinian was haunted by nightmares for months. Although the organizers reassured everyone that he’s still alive, only Ning Sinian understood the truth—the woman embracing the boy was actually his mother. His longing to be held in her arms was no different from longing to embrace death. The painting was a veiled expression of his suicidal thoughts.

Terrified, Ning Sinian tightened his control over the young man. If Wei Xiyan disappeared from his sight for more than three minutes, cold sweat would bead on his forehead, and he would become extremely anxious.

Zhao Jun, who was frequently ordered to go find him, often grumbled to himself that his boss was seriously ill.

At this moment, Ning Sinian’s face was dark as he stared at the screen, watching the man and woman interact harmoniously. The phone pressed against his ear creaked under his tightening grip.

“Can you bake cookies? My nephew loves them,” Zhou Yunsheng asked, looking at the young woman. Yes, this was the long-awaited female lead.

“I can! Would you like me to bake some for you and the child right now?” The girl’s cheeks flushed slightly, and her eyes sparkled. Because of The Way Home, she had fallen in love with Wei Xiyan three years ago. She never expected that he would be her future employer.

“Sure. The kitchen has everything you need—just help yourself,” Zhou Yunsheng gestured toward the cabinets.

The girl eagerly nodded and was just about to put on an apron when Zhao Jun strode in and said in a deep voice, “Mr. Wei, the boss just called. He said the housekeeper has already been hired, so you don’t need to worry about it. You can continue painting—I’ll escort this young lady out.” Without waiting for a response, he firmly led the girl out of the Ning residence.

Not long after, a new housekeeper arrived at the Ning residence—an elderly woman of sixty-five, her face wrinkled like dried orange peel.

Zhou Yunsheng scrutinized her from head to toe, cursing pervert in his mind but letting a smirk slip onto his lips.













